FBIS4-1480 "drafr083_cs94003" FBIS-AFR-94-083-S Daily Report 29 Apr 1994 REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA Third Day of Voting Begins `Slowly' in Homelands Third Day of Voting Begins `Slowly' in Homelands MB2904075194 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0732 GMT 29 Apr 94 MB2904075194 Johannesburg SAPA English BFN [Text] Johannesburg April 29 SAPA -- Voting in KwaZulu, Gazankulu, Lebowa and Venda started off slowly on Friday [29 April] morning with queues shorter than the last two days, reports SABC [South African Broadcasting Corporation] radio news. Among them are people also queuing for temporary votercards. Voting has been extended until 7PM on Friday in the four regions, along with Ciskei. In Durban, Independent Electoral Commission liaison officer Mr Glen Mcdougall, said that no problems were expected at KwaZulu polling stations. He added that the number of voters in Natal-KwaZulu could be more than the 4.5 million estimated earlier.
